1. c4{ Welcome to Part 3 of the Neo-Catalan! For those who don't know me, I'm Sam Shankland, a 2700+ player and a longtime Chessable Author. I have done 9 other opening courses here on Chessable in the past, most notably The Neo-Catalan parts 1 and 2. With part 3, we complete the repertoire by preparing ourselves for Black's most principled response to 1.  c4  in 1...  e5 . }( { • }1.e4 { The whole premise of our repertoire is to try to get a Reversed Dragon. Here, let's see White's best options in the Dragon proper. }1...c5 2.Nf3 g6 { This move would be the most analagous to our repertoire. Now, White has a few good options, but the one I find the most convincing is the Maroczy Bind. }3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Bg7 { If it were Black to play here, he could play  Nb8 - c6  to threaten the knight on  d4 . Then, White would not be in time to properly defend it and also get  c2 - c4  in. Instead, with White to play, he can set up a Maroczy. }5.c4! Nc6 6.Be3 Nf6 { White really should play  Nb1 - c3  to defend  e4 . Nothing else makes much sense. }7.Nc3 { And now we see that White's pawn made it to  c4 . If it had been back on  c2 , it would be there to stay because he needs to put the knight on  c3 . A tempo matters! } )( { • }1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 d6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 g6 6.Be3 Bg7 7.f3 { This is known as the Yugoslav Attack, and it is an extremely dangerous line for Black. }7...O-O 8.Qd2 Nc6 { A tempo means everything. With Black to move in this position,  d6 - d5  would immediately give him a nice game. As is, both  O-O-O  and  Bc4  are probably better for White objectively, and if something goes wrong for Black, he will be mated immediately. } )
1. e5{ I am advocating playing 2.  g3 . This is very consistent with the rest of the repertoire, and the whole concept of the Neo-Catalan is to open with 1.  c4 , bring our bishop to  g2 , and exert pressure along the long diagonal without pushing  d2 - d4  so soon.     In Part 1, I showed how in all of the lines where Black is trying to pretend he is facing 1.  d4 , White gets a lot of extra options and possibilities that I think make a Catalan setup more menacing than it would otherwise be with a 1.  d4  move order. However, nothing in chess theory comes for free, and 1.  c4  opens up two new cans of worms in 1...  c5  and 1...  e5 .     In Part 2, I focused on the Symmetrical English with 1...  c5 , which I have always thought of as a very solid line for Black, and actually the one I would least like to face after opening with 1.  c4 .     Now, it's time to face 1...  e5 . This is the most common move, and the most principled one. Black tries to immediately take a share of the center in a way that opens up lines for more of his pieces than our first move does, and voluntarily enters the Reversed Sicilian. It's largely accepted that after 1.  e4 , the Sicilian is Black's most combative response, leading to extremely complicated and interesting positions. Now, we get to play a Sicilian with a tempo up!     For anyone who studied my Classical Sicilian course, you will know that I was a big believer in putting the bishop on  g7  whenever possible. Indeed, in many of White's sidelines and less critical options, this is where the bishop went. But in the big mainlines, I had to ultimately accept that we had to develop the bishop to  e7  instead, as playing a Dragon and allowing the Yugoslav attack was not my cup of tea. If not for the Yugoslav Attack, I think the Dragon would be far and away Black's best option against 1.  e4 .     The existence of the Yugoslav Attack instead turns the Dragon into a very risky and arguably second rate opening. Some players try the Accelerated Dragon as a means of avoiding the Yugoslav Attack, but this allows the Maroczy Bind, which also is not fun for Black.      In our present repertoire, White gets to play 2.  g3  and place his bishop on  g2  without fearing any of the opposite side castling options. Black will not be able to play a Reversed Yugoslav Attack, and he will not be able to play a Reversed Maroczy Bind. If the Dragon is a fantastic opening except for exactly these two options, and we get to now play this opening without worrying about them, and we get an extra tempo, I think White has every right to fight for an advantage.     Finally, I'd like to mention that just like I said in Part 1, I very strongly recommend getting the video to go along with the MoveTrainer. The whole course is based upon playing a reversed Dragon, and there are countless times where I have to flip the board around, show why the same plan does not work if Black were playing the Dragon against 1.  e4 , and how we can make use of the extra tempo. This is extremely important to understanding the repertoire on the whole, and while I have done my best to explain it in the text and MoveTrainer, the video is far and away the best tool possible to explain these themes and they cannot be done proper justice without it. }
2. g3{ Now, Black has a ton of ways that he can set up his pieces, all of which are interesting. It takes some understanding of important subtleties for White to handle the resulting positions well, but I have done my best to keep it as straightforward as possible. One nice point, for example, is there is not a single spot in this entire course where the  b1 -knight goes to any square other than  c3 ! Timing the development of the knight is tricky in some spots, but it never goes anywhere else. All of this stuff is covered in detail in the theory section. For now, let's see why Black can't do his most ambitious options. }
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. Nc3{ Black probably should play  Nd5 - b6  here. }
5. Be6{ This would be most consistent with the most ambitious setups against the Dragon, aiming for either the Maroczy or the Yugoslav Attack. }
6. Nf3{ Black is forced to play  Nc6  to keep his pawn safe. No Maroczy for you! }
6. Nc6
7. O-O
7. f6{ Black is already worse, but this only adds to his problems.  f7 - f6  is the Yugoslav move. And now White gets a normal Dragon position up two tempos - one for being White, and another for not playing  d2 - d3  first. }
8. d4{ Black is in big trouble. }
