1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. g6{ Setting up some kind of Reversed Closed Sicilian is a very reasonable plan for Black. In the proper Closed Sicilian, Black equalizes easily, but should not be better, and the position is quiet enough that one could argue that a single tempo should not make a huge difference. Still, I think we can put Black's position under some pressure. }( { • }2...Nf6 3.Bg2 Nc6 4.Nc3 g6 5.Nf3 Bg7 6.d4 { This transposes to the 2...  g6  move order. } )( { • }2...Nc6 { This move order doesn't have any indipendent value. }3.Nc3 g6 4.Bg2 Bg7 5.e3 { And we transpose to the 4...  Nc6  positions. } )
3. Bg2{ It is important to understand some points about how we want to set up our pieces. First of all, our default next move is  Nb1 - c3 . As mentioned in the introduction, this knight never goes anywhere else. Now that Black has committed to putting his bishop on  g7 , we can bring the knight to  c3  without any discussion. This will leave us flexible with the rest of our pieces. Next, whenever Black plays  c7 - c6 , we generally want to respond with  e2 - e4  and set up a Botvinnik.     Black's best plan then tends to be to play  c6 - c5  to reach a locked structure, and then we will have a symmetrical position with two extra tempos. Black will still be solid, but the tempos have to count for something. If Black ever plays  Nb8 - c6 , we should immediately be looking to push  e2 - e3  and develop our knight to  e2 . Part of the reason for this is that by putting the knight on  c6 , Black has given up on playing  c7 - c6  and aiming for  d7 - d5 , which means we no longer need to put our pawn on  e4 . If Black ever plays ... Nf6  without pushing  f7 - f5  first, our knight should go to  f3 . This is because we will be able to play  d2 - d4 , and Black will not be able to respond with  e5 - e4  because he will be missing the necessary  f5 -pawn to keep the  e4 -pawn protected.     Finally, if Black ever castles too early, always be on the lookout for  h2 - h4 . This can help things become interesting! }
3. Bg7
4. Nc3{ In general, we almost always want to put our knight on  c3  in this repertoire. Often, we delay moving it there because of some ... c6 +... d5  or early ... Bb4  idea, but once Black has clearly advertised that neither of these are possibilities any more, the knight can go to its best square. }
4. Nf6{ Now, much like we also saw in the Classical Sicilian, I think White's knight will make a lot of sense on  f3  if Black has foregone any hope of  f7 - f5 . }
5. Nf3
5. Nc6( 5...d6 6.d4 { This will transpose to the King's Indian positions covered in Part 1. } )
6. d4
6. exd4
7. Nxd4
7. O-O
8. O-O
8. Re8
9. Nc2{ White looks better with the extra space. Next up is  Qd1 - d2 ,  b2 - b3 , and  Bc1 - b2 . }
