[Black "2...Nf6 3.Bg2 Bc5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. Bc5{ This has been a trendy move in the last several years. Black develops his bishop to  c5  and remains flexible about the rest of his development scheme, waiting for us to decide how we want to place our pieces. }
4. Nc3{ This is certainly White's boldest move, aiming to complicate the game right away. We are ready for  Ng1 - f3  to come next, and we have not given up on playing  d2 - d4  in one move to take the entire center. }( 4.d3 { In recent times, this has emerged as White's main move. I dislike it because after }4...O-O 5.Nf3 Nc6! { Black is ready for  d7 - d5  to come next, getting us into a version of the reverse open Sicilian where Black was able to leave the knight on  d5  and play  Bc5 . I believe Black is totally fine there, and it is one of the biggest reasons that I prefer a 2.  g3  move order. } )
4. c6{ This is Black's critical response. His argument is that unlike what we say in the sections on 2.  g3   c6  or 2.  g3   Nf6  3.  Bg2   c6 , in this case we are unable to play  Ng1 - f3  and meet  e5 - e4  with  Nf3 - d4 . As such, our knight will become sidelined. Still, I will not be dissuaded so easily. }( { • }4...O-O 5.Nf3 { Black has nothing better than  Nc6  here, transposing to the Karpov system. } )( { • }4...d6 5.Nf3 { This will transpose to the Karpov System as well. } )
5. Nf3{ This is surely the most testing move. Now, Black is immediately forced into complications. }
5. e4{ Nothing else makes any sense. }
6. Nh4
6. d5
7. cxd5
7. cxd5{ Now, our knight is sidelined on  h4  and in some danger of being trapped by  g7 - g5 . we need to contest the center right away. }
8. d3{ White hits at the center directly and prevents  g7 - g5 . if Black's  e4 -pawn is successfully undermined or exchanged, our knight will be forever safe and Black will be left with an isolani. He is forced to provoke a fight right away. }( 8.O-O? { This is too slow. I actually played it myself in a blitz game when I forgot the move order for White, and already after }8...h6! { with  g7 - g5  coming next, White is worse. I won the game by some miracle (it was blitz after all), but this is not how you want to play chess! } )
8. Ng4{ Nothing else makes any sense. Black needs to immediately provoke a confrontation to avoid a statically unpleasant position. }
9. O-O
9. g5{ Our knight is trapped. Now, things get very messy. }
10. d4{ White has other reasonable options, but I like this one the best. The point is that we attack Black's bishop, forcing it away from the  f2 -pawn, and then we can follow up with  h2 - h3 . }( 10.h3?! { White is not ready for this just yet. }10...Nxf2! { I don't like that this move is possible. } )
10. Bb6{ So far, this move has not seen any play, but it doesn't look so stupid to me, so I thought I should cover it all the same. It's important to note that we have to handle it very differently than we would handle  Bb4  or  Be7 . }
11. Nf3( { I like this move a lot. It seems brazen to simply place the knight on a square where it can simply be taken, but we can take advantage of the position of Black's bishop. }11.h3? { Sadly, we cannot continue in the same manner as we would against  Be7  or  Bb4 . }11...gxh4 12.hxg4 Nc6!∓ { The bishop is really good on  b6  here, and White has a hard time defending  d4  and keeping up the initiative. Black is much better. It is a problem that we can never play  f2 - f3  to try to blow up the f-file, as we would be slaughtered along the  a7 - g1  diagonal. } )
11. exf3( { This is not the best move, but obviously one we should be ready for. }11...h6 { is analyzed starting  here . } )
12. exf3
12. Nf6
13. Bxg5{ Of course. Black's knight is in a very problematic pin that he cannot break, as White's bishop will always be totally safe on  h4 . In the meantime,  f3 - f4  is coming to open up an attack on the  d5 -pawn, and Black's king will never find safety. The machine only gives White a slight to moderate edge, but I think a human would go down hard with Black. }
