[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Be7{ This move has picked up some popularity as of late, and it was recently played against me by Aryan Tari. }
3. Nc3{ I like this move order, remaining flexible with the  f1 -bishop. We always bring the knight to  c3  in this repertoire, and now seems like a good moment because we are not worried about  Bf8 - b4 . }
3. f5
4. d4{ White tries to take the entire center. }
4. d6
5. Bh3{ I like this move a lot, putting pressure on the  f5 -pawn. Black has a hard time keeping the position together. }
5. Nf6{ Obviously, this move could be considered as well. Black brings out a new piece, but now White can make use of a nice point. }
6. Nf3{ Normally,  Ng1 - f3  might look like it should not be how White wants to develop his pieces. It looks like it walks straight into  e5 - e4  with a gain of tempo. But, we can take advantage of the knight going to  f6 . }
6. Nc6{ This feels very human to me, aiming to play in the style of the Classical Dutch. Black bolsters his  e5 -pawn. But, it comes at a price. }
7. d5{ Normally in the Classical Dutch, Black would want to have his pawn on  a5  so that he could meet this move with  Nc6 - b4 . Now, he does not have that luxury. }
7. Nb8{ This feels like the most human move to me, since I really do not see a future for the knight on  a5 . It's a good sign for us that it is a big mistake! }
8. Ng5{ Not especially subtle. The knight is coming to  e6 . }
8. O-O
9. Ne6
9. Bxe6
10. dxe6{ Black has to defend the  f5 -pawn. }
10. g6
11. Bh6
11. Re8
12. e4{ White has other good moves, but I like this one for its simplicity. He hits the  f5 -pawn, forcing it to get out of the way of the  h3 -bishop, and the  e6 -pawn will survive. }
12. Nxe4
13. Nxe4
13. fxe4
14. O-O{ White will take back the  e4 -pawn whenever he wants it, and Black is much worse thanks to the bishop pair, the passed pawn on  e6 , and the king on  g8  lacking any long term stability. }
