[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Be7{ This move has picked up some popularity as of late, and it was recently played against me by Aryan Tari. }
3. Nc3{ I like this move order, remaining flexible with the  f1 -bishop. We always bring the knight to  c3  in this repertoire, and now seems like a good moment because we are not worried about  Bf8 - b4 . }
3. f5
4. d4{ White tries to take the entire center. }
4. d6
5. Bh3{ I like this move a lot, putting pressure on the  f5 -pawn. Black has a hard time keeping the position together. }
5. Nf6{ Obviously, this move could be considered as well. Black brings out a new piece, but now White can make use of a nice point. }
6. Nf3{ Normally,  Ng1 - f3  might look like it should not be how White wants to develop his pieces. It looks like it walks straight into  e5 - e4  with a gain of tempo. But, we can take advantage of the knight going to  f6 . }
6. Ne4{ My computer thinks this is the best move. It looks a bit weird to me but it is hard to argue with machines in today's era. }
7. Nd5{ This seems simplest to me. Going pawn grabbing on  e5  was possible, but the queenside structure would have been shattered. Here, White has a nice structural advantage and can continue with  O-O ,  b2 - b3 , and  Bc1 - b2 . }
