6. Nge7
7. Nge2
7. O-O
8. O-O{ White has an easy built in plan of  Ra1 - b1  and  b2 - b4 - b5 . With the knight on  e2  like this, I really don't buy Black's hope for any kingside counterplay. He will never get his pawn to  f4 . It's important to understand that the plan of pushing  b4 - b5  makes a lot more sense when Black's  g8 -knight develops to  e7 , as we see here. It means that when  b4 - b5  comes, the other knight lacks a good square to retreat to.     This position has been seen a lot in blitz games, but almost never in classical, and for good reason. White's position seems easy enough to play and his results are very good. We will see a nice effort from  Tsydypov  in the illustrative games section. }
