5. d3{ I like this patient move. Now, Black is sort of out of waiting moves. For White, we should understand that if Black is able to play  c7 - c6  and  d7 - d5 , he will have a very easy position. As such, we want to make sure to meet the move  c7 - c6  with  e2 - e4 , setting up a Botvinnik. But, we don't want to play  e2 - e4  if Black does not commit to  c7 - c6  first! Luckily for us, Black is out of good waiting moves. }
5. O-O( { This feels like Black's most annoying move to me. He asks us to make up our mind on pushing  e2 - e4  or not, and what to do about developing the  g1 -knight. Then, he will coordinate his pieces well in response. But, luckily for us, we can take advantage of Black showing his cards here as well. }5...Nbc6 6.e3 { transposes to the 4...  Nc6  setups. } )
6. h4{ Why not? Black has castled right into a potential attack. A thrust like this only works well when you are sure that you can contain the center, and here, White surely can. }
6. c6{ Whenever you attack on a flank, you should always be ready for a counterattack in the center. Here, we are. }
7. h5
7. d5{ The machine does not like this move, but I cannot imagine a human playing anything else right after pushing  c7 - c6 . }
8. hxg6
8. hxg6
9. Bh6{ It almost feels like we are playing a dragon. Remove the guard, play for mate! }
9. Bxh6( { Black should take this one right away and at least force us to take back with the rook instead of the queen. }9...Be6 10.Qd2! {  Bxg7  followed by  Qh6  is not messing around. Black would have been better advised to take on  h6 . } )
10. Rxh6
10. Kg7
11. Qd2
11. Rh8{ This stops the mating threats, but does not save the game. }
12. Rxh8
12. Qxh8
13. cxd5{ White wins a healthy pawn, and Black is totally busted. }
