1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nc6{ This move is obviously very playable. But the chapter here is very short, as most lines will end up transposing somewhere else. }
3. Bg2
3. f5{ If Black is looking for an independent variation within 2...  Nc6 , this is surely his best move. He plays  f7 - f5  at a moment when we cannot respond with  d2 - d4 , and tried to play some kind of reversed Grand Prix Attack. It's far from stupid and I faced it against both Sasikiran and Mareco some time ago, scoring 0.5/2. That said, with good understanding, I think we can still fight for an edge. }
4. Nc3
4. Nf6
5. b3{ I like this move a lot. White remains patient with the  g1 -knight, does not commit to  e2 - e3  yet, and starts off with putting his bishop on  g2 . }( 5.e3 { In general I think this is White's most ambitious setup, but I am not thrilled with the position after }5...e4! 6.d3 Bb4 7.Nge2 d5! { When I once lost a tough game to Krishnan Sasikiran. White still can fight for an edge here if he plays better than I did, but I prefer the text. } )
5. Bc5
6. Bb2
6. O-O
7. e3{ Now and only now, we play  e2 - e3 . White no longer has to fear  e5 - e4 . }
7. f4{ This would be a typical Grand Prix move, but now we can take the fight to him on the kingside. }
8. gxf4
8. exf4
9. Nd5{ Who is attacking whom here? }
