[White "4) Karpov System "]
[Black "4...d6 5.e3 Nge7"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nc6( { • }2...Bc5 3.Nc3 { Black doesn't have much in the way of independent options here. I would expect ... Nc6  to come, which will promptly transpose to the mainline Karpov System that we will see shortly. }3...Nc6 4.Bg2 { Transposes to the mainline. } )( { • }2...Bc5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Nf3 Nc6 5.Bg2 { This transposes to the mainline as well. } )
3. Bg2
3. Bc5{ The Karpov System was very popular for a long time. It went through a phase where it was rarely seen, and nowadays, I am seeing it more often again. Black's strategy is relatively simple. He brings out his pieces to normal looking squares, does not try to do anything too special, he generally will allow us to advance  d2 - d4 , and hope that eventually our  d4 -pawn will prove annoying to maintain.     It is a very solid system, and one where if things go wrong for Black, generally he will only be a little worse, and one inaccurate move from our end will immediately allow him comfortable equality. There are a lot of subtle differences in the move orders. White should be careful and precise, but I do think I managed to fight for an edge. }
4. Nc3{ We are no longer worried about the bishop coming to  b4 , so the knight on  c3  should be fine. Now, a traditional Karpov system would involve putting the knight on  f6 . This surely should be considered the main move, but Black has other possible coordinations as well. }
4. d6{ This is actually Black's most popular move. It makes a lot of sense, it is very clear that he will need to play  d7 - d6  at some point, so he might as well do it now, and wait on choosing between  e7  and  f6  for the knight later on. }
5. e3{ I like this move order the best. Much like Black just did to us, we ask him for a move before deciding what to do with our  g1 -knight. Against anything except for  f7 - f5 , we will want to put the knight on  f3 . }
5. Nge7( 5...h5? { This plan does exist for Black, but it really only makes sense once White's knight is on the  e2  square. After the obvious }6.Nf3! { Black will not play  h5 - h4 , and his position looks pretty dumb. } )
6. Nf3{ Black's knight on  e7  looks misplaced to me. White has the same plan as always:  O-O ,  b3 , play for  d4  later. It's surprising to me that this move has only seen play in two games compared to 169 with  Nge2 , as I believe the knight is much better placed on  f3 . We will see an  interesting encounter  in the illustrative games section that shows the middlegame in more detail. }
