7. d4{ Now, since Black is considerably less well developed than he would be with moves like  Ng8 - f6  and  O-O  played instead of  f7 - f5  and  a7 - a6 , he is unable to retreat the bishop to  a7  to maintain the tension. }
7. Bb4{ It is a bad sign for Black that this weird looking move is best. Normally, his point in the Karpov system is to try to keep the bishop on the  a7 - g1  diagonal, and this is further exaggerated by the move  a7 - a6 , which is basically just wasted time if the bishop was going to go to  b4  anyway. Still, Black's play is not so ridiculous, and we have to be somewhat wary of getting into a bad Nimzo structure if he can take on  c3  next. Luckily, I think White is good to go with simple moves. }
8. O-O{ When in doubt, get castled. Now,  Nc3 - d5  is on the way, and I really think Black should take on  c3 . }
8. Bxc3( 8...e4 9.Nd2 { Black has to take on  c3  all the same, transposing to 9...  e4  - see the notes on Black's next move. } )
9. bxc3
9. Nf6{ Now, White should be very energetic. We are stuck with a bad bishop on  c1  and a weak  c4 -pawn, and if Black can complete his development without anything bad happening, I would think we would be worse. Luckily, we are not out of resources. }( 9...e4?! { This is too soon and too ambitious. }10.Nd2± { Strategically, White's position is pretty suspect long term, but that hardly matters. Black is way behind in development, and he will suffer quite a bit once we blow up the center with  f2 - f3  and  e3 - e4 . } )
10. Ba3{ I like this move a lot. It looks weird and a bit aimless to put the bishop on the  a3 - f8  diagonal since Black is blunting it with the  d6 -pawn, but there is a method to our madness. First of all, Black is unable to castle thanks to the hanging  e5 -pawn. But if he is not going to castle, what will he do? }
10. Qe7{ This move feels very human to me, aiming to overprotect the  e5 -pawn and castle next. But it comes at a price. }
11. c5{ And now we see the point. Since Black has placed the queen on the  e7 -square, Black is unable to close the center with  e5 - e4  followed by  d6 - d5 . }
11. d5{ Now, Black is threatening  e5 - e4  next, when we would be in big trouble. But we can blow up the position for our bishops first. }
12. dxe5
12. Nxe5
13. Nxe5
13. Qxe5
14. Qc1{ White has other good moves, but I like this one for its simplicity.  c3 - c4  and  Ba3 - b2  are coming soon, and the bishops will ravage the board. }
