9. Nf6{ Now, White should be very energetic. We are stuck with a bad bishop on  c1  and a weak  c4 -pawn, and if Black can complete his development without anything bad happening, I would think we would be worse. Luckily, we are not out of resources. }( 9...e4?! { This is too soon and too ambitious. }10.Nd2± { Strategically, White's position is pretty suspect long term, but that hardly matters. Black is way behind in development, and he will suffer quite a bit once we blow up the center with  f2 - f3  and  e3 - e4 . } )
10. Ba3{ I like this move a lot. It looks weird and a bit aimless to put the bishop on the  a3 - f8  diagonal since Black is blunting it with the  d6 -pawn, but there is a method to our madness. First of all, Black is unable to castle thanks to the hanging  e5 -pawn. But if he is not going to castle, what will he do? }
10. Qe7{ This move feels very human to me, aiming to overprotect the  e5 -pawn and castle next. But it comes at a price. }
11. c5{ And now we see the point. Since Black has placed the queen on the  e7 -square, Black is unable to close the center with  e5 - e4  followed by  d6 - d5 . }
11. e4
12. cxd6( { This move was made possible by Black's queen going to  e7 . He is not able to take on  f3 . }12.Nd2? d5∓ { Black closed the center and shut down our bishops. This is a total disaster that should be avoided at all costs. } )
12. cxd6
13. Nd2
13. Be6
14. c4{ White's dark squared bishop is a fine piece all of a sudden! Black is in big trouble thanks to his numerous weaknesses. Moves like  Ra1 - b1  and  f2 - f3  are coming next. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Karpov System "]
[Black "4...d6 5.e3 a6 #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nc6( { • }2...Bc5 3.Nc3 { Black doesn't have much in the way of independent options here. I would expect ... Nc6  to come, which will promptly transpose to the mainline Karpov System that we will see shortly. }3...Nc6 4.Bg2 { Transposes to the mainline. } )( { • }2...Bc5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Nf3 Nc6 5.Bg2 { This transposes to the mainline as well. } )
3. Bg2
3. Bc5{ The Karpov System was very popular for a long time. It went through a phase where it was rarely seen, and nowadays, I am seeing it more often again. Black's strategy is relatively simple. He brings out his pieces to normal looking squares, does not try to do anything too special, he generally will allow us to advance  d2 - d4 , and hope that eventually our  d4 -pawn will prove annoying to maintain.     It is a very solid system, and one where if things go wrong for Black, generally he will only be a little worse, and one inaccurate move from our end will immediately allow him comfortable equality. There are a lot of subtle differences in the move orders. White should be careful and precise, but I do think I managed to fight for an edge. }
4. Nc3{ We are no longer worried about the bishop coming to  b4 , so the knight on  c3  should be fine. Now, a traditional Karpov system would involve putting the knight on  f6 . This surely should be considered the main move, but Black has other possible coordinations as well. }
4. d6{ This is actually Black's most popular move. It makes a lot of sense, it is very clear that he will need to play  d7 - d6  at some point, so he might as well do it now, and wait on choosing between  e7  and  f6  for the knight later on. }
5. e3{ I like this move order the best. Much like Black just did to us, we ask him for a move before deciding what to do with our  g1 -knight. Against anything except for  f7 - f5 , we will want to put the knight on  f3 . }
5. a6{ This has been Black's most common move in the past. He really is trying to play the waiting game, asking us to put the knight on  e2  so that he can play a plan with  h7 - h5 . While the machine seems to think White is better even if he 'falls' for the trap and plays  Nge2  here, I like remaining consistent and putting the knight on  f3  any time Black has not pushed  f7 - f5 . Since we are out of waiting moves, this means we have to play  Ng1 - f3  here. }( 5...Nf6 6.Nf3 { transposes to 4...  Nf6 . } )
6. Nf3
6. f5{ Whenever we place the knight on  f3 , it always becomes a bit more sensible for Black to play a plan with  f7 - f5 . This position is no exception, but I still think White has every right to fight for an advantage. }
7. d4{ Now, since Black is considerably less well developed than he would be with moves like  Ng8 - f6  and  O-O  played instead of  f7 - f5  and  a7 - a6 , he is unable to retreat the bishop to  a7  to maintain the tension. }
7. Bb4{ It is a bad sign for Black that this weird looking move is best. Normally, his point in the Karpov system is to try to keep the bishop on the  a7 - g1  diagonal, and this is further exaggerated by the move  a7 - a6 , which is basically just wasted time if the bishop was going to go to  b4  anyway. Still, Black's play is not so ridiculous, and we have to be somewhat wary of getting into a bad Nimzo structure if he can take on  c3  next. Luckily, I think White is good to go with simple moves. }
8. O-O{ When in doubt, get castled. Now,  Nc3 - d5  is on the way, and I really think Black should take on  c3 . }
8. Bxc3( 8...e4 9.Nd2 { Black has to take on  c3  all the same, transposing to 9...  e4  - see the notes on Black's next move. } )
9. bxc3
9. Nf6{ Now, White should be very energetic. We are stuck with a bad bishop on  c1  and a weak  c4 -pawn, and if Black can complete his development without anything bad happening, I would think we would be worse. Luckily, we are not out of resources. }( 9...e4?! { This is too soon and too ambitious. }10.Nd2± { Strategically, White's position is pretty suspect long term, but that hardly matters. Black is way behind in development, and he will suffer quite a bit once we blow up the center with  f2 - f3  and  e3 - e4 . } )
10. Ba3{ I like this move a lot. It looks weird and a bit aimless to put the bishop on the  a3 - f8  diagonal since Black is blunting it with the  d6 -pawn, but there is a method to our madness. First of all, Black is unable to castle thanks to the hanging  e5 -pawn. But if he is not going to castle, what will he do? }
10. e4{ This move is a lot better than it was a second ago, but I still think it fails to equalize. }
11. Nd2
11. O-O
12. f3
12. exf3
13. Qxf3{ Black won't be demolished here the same way he would have been if he had pushed  e5 - e4  without including  Ng8 - f6  and  Bc1 - a3  first. Still, with  Ra1 - e1  and  e3 - e4  on the way, White is definitely for choice. }
