5. Nf3{ For a long time, the most popular way for White to develop his pieces was to coordinate with  e2 - e3  and  Ng1 - e2 . This does have some merit to it, but I actually found that I like the knight on  f3  better. This is because down the road, it is putting pressure on the  e5 -pawn and Black will be unable to regroup the  c6 -knight to  e7  as a result. We will see this later on as well. For the most part, we are planning on developing the knight to  f3  in this section, except for a couple of really fringe and extreme circumstances. }
5. d5( { In modern times, I could easily see a human making this move. It might seem like a clever move order to push  d7 - d5  because when we take it, after }6.Nxd5 { , we will reach a position in the reverse open Sicilian that I specifically wanted to avoid. Luckily for us, we have a nice option to immediately inflict punishment. } )
6. Nxe5{ White starts a tactical sequence that will end in his favor. }
6. Bxf2+
7. Kxf2
7. Nxe5
8. cxd5{ White's king is a little sketchy, but he is not facing any direct threats. An extra central pawn and a healthy bishop pair matter! }
