2. Nc6( { • }2...Bc5 3.Nc3 { Black doesn't have much in the way of independent options here. I would expect ... Nc6  to come, which will promptly transpose to the mainline Karpov System that we will see shortly. }3...Nc6 4.Bg2 { Transposes to the mainline. } )( { • }2...Bc5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Nf3 Nc6 5.Bg2 { This transposes to the mainline as well. } )
3. Bg2
3. Bc5{ The Karpov System was very popular for a long time. It went through a phase where it was rarely seen, and nowadays, I am seeing it more often again. Black's strategy is relatively simple. He brings out his pieces to normal looking squares, does not try to do anything too special, he generally will allow us to advance  d2 - d4 , and hope that eventually our  d4 -pawn will prove annoying to maintain.     It is a very solid system, and one where if things go wrong for Black, generally he will only be a little worse, and one inaccurate move from our end will immediately allow him comfortable equality. There are a lot of subtle differences in the move orders. White should be careful and precise, but I do think I managed to fight for an edge. }
4. Nc3{ We are no longer worried about the bishop coming to  b4 , so the knight on  c3  should be fine. Now, a traditional Karpov system would involve putting the knight on  f6 . This surely should be considered the main move, but Black has other possible coordinations as well. }
4. Nf6
5. Nf3{ For a long time, the most popular way for White to develop his pieces was to coordinate with  e2 - e3  and  Ng1 - e2 . This does have some merit to it, but I actually found that I like the knight on  f3  better. This is because down the road, it is putting pressure on the  e5 -pawn and Black will be unable to regroup the  c6 -knight to  e7  as a result. We will see this later on as well. For the most part, we are planning on developing the knight to  f3  in this section, except for a couple of really fringe and extreme circumstances. }
5. O-O{ Delaying  d6  is not senseless, but I don't think it changes a ton. }
6. O-O
6. Re8{ If Black is hell bent on not playing  d7 - d6 , I would think this should be his best move. I don't think it does much for him. }( { • }6...d5?! 7.Nxe5! { Again, this proves powerful. } )( { • }6...d6 7.e3 { This transposes to the mainline. } )
7. e3{ My computer is now adamant that Black should play  d7 - d6 , transposing back into the main lines. Still, I think it is important to know what to do if Black pushes  d7 - d5  instead. }
7. d5( 7...d6 { it's again a transposition, while }7...e4?! { loses a pawn to }8.Ng5!±  )
8. cxd5
8. Nxd5
9. Nxd5
9. Qxd5{ Now, Black is strategically doing very well, but we have a nice tactical resource available. }
10. Ng5{ Black's queen is hit, and he will have to deal with  Qd1 - c2  next and have a lot of hanging stuff. }
10. Qc4{ This feels like the most human move for Black to me. Stopping  Qd1 - c2  is important. But it does not solve all of Black's problems. }( 10...Qd7 11.Qc2! { Black faces the same problems on  c5  and  h7 . }11...Qf5 12.Qxc5 { This transposes to the 10...  Qd6  line. } )
11. f4{ This energetic move puts Black in bad shape. He cannot take on  f4 , and he is hard pressed to deal with the basic idea of  f4xe5 , not only opening the f-file but also getting White ready for  d2 - d4  to come. Black is much worse, but we should definitely know what we are doing. }
11. Bf5{ The computer also offers this move, which feels a bit inhuman to me - I would definitely expect to see  h6  instead. Black places his bishop in the line of fire. }
12. b3{ Again, this move proves powerful. Black's queen should be kicked off the  c4 -square. }
12. Qd3{ This surely does not equalize, but it is the toughest move to deal with. White should be ready. }
13. g4{ This is a very clever refutation. By placing the queen on  d3 , Black is denying himself  Bf5 - c2 . }
13. exf4
14. gxf5
14. Qxf5
15. Qh5
15. h6{ Now, after some fireworks, it is time to simplify. }
16. Qxf7+
16. Qxf7
17. Nxf7
17. Kxf7
18. Rxf4+{ White is much better thanks to his monster bishops and central pawn mass. Next up could even be  Rf4 - c4  to win material on the c-file. }
