10. exd4{ This is probably Black's best move. }
11. Nxd4{ As usual, we take with the knight on  d4 . }
11. Nxd4( 11...Bxd4? { This was seen in the only game to reach this position so far, and it is a serious strategic misunderstanding. After }12.exd4⩲ { White is pleasantly better with  d4 - d5  coming soon. Normally, it is not advisable to push  d4 - d5  in this structure since it wakes up Black's dark squared bishop, but here the bishop is gone! We will see a  nice effort from Potkin  in the illustrative games section. } )
12. exd4{ Black still has some problems to solve here thanks to the loose pawn on  b7 . }
12. c6{ This feels like the most human move to me, blunting the long diagonal, but now White has an important idea. }
13. d5{ Black is left in a tough spot where he has to choose between giving himself a lousy structure and pacifying his own bishop with  c6 - c5 . }
13. Qd7( { This is probably Black's best move, but not a happy one. }13...c5?! { This only makes matters worse. }14.h3! { White will continue with  g3 - g4 , regroup his knight to  g3 , and then eventually push for  f2 - f4 . The kingside attack will become very dangerous, and Black's bishop on  b6  is really lousy. } )
14. dxc6
14. bxc6
15. Na4{ Black's bishop is kicked off the long diagonal. }
15. Bd8
16. Qd4{ White is pleasantly better and has easy play against the hanging central pawns.  Ra1 - d1  comes next. }
