[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Karpov System "]
[Black "4...Nf6 5.Nf3 d6 #18"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nc6( { • }2...Bc5 3.Nc3 { Black doesn't have much in the way of independent options here. I would expect ... Nc6  to come, which will promptly transpose to the mainline Karpov System that we will see shortly. }3...Nc6 4.Bg2 { Transposes to the mainline. } )( { • }2...Bc5 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Nf3 Nc6 5.Bg2 { This transposes to the mainline as well. } )
3. Bg2
3. Bc5{ The Karpov System was very popular for a long time. It went through a phase where it was rarely seen, and nowadays, I am seeing it more often again. Black's strategy is relatively simple. He brings out his pieces to normal looking squares, does not try to do anything too special, he generally will allow us to advance  d2 - d4 , and hope that eventually our  d4 -pawn will prove annoying to maintain.     It is a very solid system, and one where if things go wrong for Black, generally he will only be a little worse, and one inaccurate move from our end will immediately allow him comfortable equality. There are a lot of subtle differences in the move orders. White should be careful and precise, but I do think I managed to fight for an edge. }
4. Nc3{ We are no longer worried about the bishop coming to  b4 , so the knight on  c3  should be fine. Now, a traditional Karpov system would involve putting the knight on  f6 . This surely should be considered the main move, but Black has other possible coordinations as well. }
4. Nf6
5. Nf3{ For a long time, the most popular way for White to develop his pieces was to coordinate with  e2 - e3  and  Ng1 - e2 . This does have some merit to it, but I actually found that I like the knight on  f3  better. This is because down the road, it is putting pressure on the  e5 -pawn and Black will be unable to regroup the  c6 -knight to  e7  as a result. We will see this later on as well. For the most part, we are planning on developing the knight to  f3  in this section, except for a couple of really fringe and extreme circumstances. }
5. d6
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. e3{ In general, I would consider this position to be the biggest and most critical one in the Karpov System. It can be reached through many move orders, and Black can easily play  h7 - h6 ,  a7 - a6 , or  Bc5 - b6  at more or less any moment earlier on, transposing to what we will see later. Now, I think it is very important for White to understand what he is playing for. There are a lot of plans available to him, but the one I like the most is as follows.     Ultimately, what White should be trying to accomplish is to push  d2 - d4  under favorable circumstances. It may look like we are ready to do so on our next move, but in fact I think this is actually not true. The problem is that as soon as we do push  d2 - d4 , Black will be able to bring his bishop to  g4 , pressuring our center and asking us to release the tension before we are ready to do so.     So, my plan is to play  b2 - b3  first. It's important to realize that while clearing the  b2 -square for the bishop is a nice bonus, this is not the main point of touching the b-pawn. Rather, we want to protect the  c4 -pawn. As long as we have not put our pawn on  d4 , it will make no sense for Black to play  Bc8 - g4 , as it will be well met with  h2 - h3 . Once we have played  b2 - b3 , we will then be ready to advance  d2 - d4  and quickly take on  e5 . Then following  Nc6xe5 , we will not need to burn a tempo on  b2 - b3  to defend the  c4 -pawn, and White will be able to retain his space advantage and a nice edge. }
7. a6{ The computer does not show a huge preference for Black, but this is certainly the move I would most expect to see from a well schooled opponent. Black anticipates that  d2 - d4  is coming, and makes sure to clear the safe  a7 -square for his bishop - this is a basic and well known theme in the Karpov System. It is second most common, but I think much harder to deal with than the more often played  Bc8 - g4 . }
8. b3{ I like this move, remaining consistent. We don't need to rush with  d2 - d4 . It will come soon enough. }
8. Ba7{ This is Black's most common move. It makes a lot of sense given that he played  a7 - a6  last move. Now,  d2 - d4  would play right into his hands with  Bc8 - g4  coming next. We should be more patient. }
9. h3{ I like this move a lot. White keeps the bishop off of  g4 , and he can hope for  d2 - d4  to come next. Once this happens, I think Black will be best advised to exchange pawns. Then, we will be happy to have not put our bishop on  b2 , as it will sit better on  e3 . }
9. Re8
10. d4{ Now, I think Black is best advised to take on  d4 . We are ready to take on  e5  next. }
10. exd4
11. Nxd4{ I like opening up the long diagonal. Now, Black should definitely take on  d4  to avoid getting a horrible structure. }
11. Nxd4
12. exd4
12. h6{ My computer insists this is best. I guess it is acutely aware of the the threats of  Bg5  at inopportune moments. }
13. Kh2{ White overprotects the  h3 -pawn. This means Black's bishop is stuck on  c8 , since he cannot hang  b7  if he can't take  h3  in response. The Catalan bishop looks nice! }
13. Rb8( 13...c6 14.d5!⩲ { Again, this works nicely. Black really does not want to bury his own bishop with  c6 - c5 , but otherwise he will be left with an isolated d-pawn. } )
14. Qd3{ I like this move, keeping Black's bishop off  f5 . Black is still solid, but has a bit less space and I'm not sure how he wants to get the  a7 -bishop back into the game. White looks a bit better. }
