8. Bc5{ This is Black's main move. He is hoping to take the knight on  e3  to get access to the  f5 -square for his other bishop to keep the  e4 -pawn safe. Now, I like a move that aims to marginally improve upon the main line. }
9. Qa4{ In almost every single game, White has chosen to put the queen on  c2  instead. In general, I find  a4  to be a more active square, and it opens up some extra possibilities. Black is surely able to push us back to  c2  right away with  b7 - b5 , but I believe this move weakens his position. }
9. Qe5{ Trying to keep the pawn defended at all costs is asking for trouble. }
10. Bg2
10. Bxe3( { • }10...b5 11.Qc2! { White transposes to a nice version of the mainline. } )( { • }10...Bd4 11.Nc2!  )
11. dxe3
11. Bf5{ Black's position looks pretty solid here. But, now White has a nice way to take advantage of his queen being on  a4  rather than  c2 . }
12. g4
12. Bg6{ If White's queen was on  c2  here, he would not have a great follow up. As is, we can immediately challenge Black's queen on  e5 , which is holding his position together. }( { • }12...b5? { It is too late for this. If Black wanted to push  b7 - b5 , he should have done it earlier, before our queen could go to  d4 . }13.Qd4+- { Black is collapsing. } )( { • }12...Bxg4 13.Nxe4± { White took the central pawn and his bishops will run rampant. Next up is  Bd2 - c3 . } )
13. Qd4{ Now, Black will not be able to prevent  g4 - g5  from coming. }
13. Qxd4
14. exd4{  g5  comes next, and Black cannot keep  e4  safe. The best he can do is grab  g4  to keep material parity, but it is still miserable. }
14. Nxg4( 14...h6 15.h4 {  g5  is coming and Black has to take on  g4  anyway. } )
15. Nxe4{ The knight is coming to  d6  next, and my computer insists upon taking it right now. }
15. Bxe4
16. Bxe4{ White is much better thanks to his bishop pair and having more pawns in the center. }
