2. c6{ With Black's second move of the game, he intends to immediately fight for the center of the board with  d7 - d5  next. The position transfers into a reversed Alapin, where White gets the free move  g2 - g3 . This tempo totally changes the character of the position. }
3. Nf3{ In the proper Alapin, I always preferred 2...  Nf6  to 2...  d5 , and when playing White in a similar position, I share the same preference. }
3. e4{ I really don't see Black playing anything else. }
4. Nd4{ Now, it is important for Black to realize that he is not simply playing a reversed Alapin. The extra tempo is huge for White! Being able to get the bishop to  g2  without any kind of disaster striking on  f2  means that White will have a much safer king than in a normal mainline Alapin, and he also will have a much easier time pressuring the  e4 -pawn. }
4. d5( 4...Nf6 5.Bg2 { Transposes to the next chapter. } )
5. cxd5
5. Qxd5{ This is very necessary. While there does exist a line in the Alapin where White takes with the queen on  d4 , it is not great and not too common. Here, it makes much more sense. The queen is better placed when it can make trouble on the somewhat loosened long diagonal, and if Black anticipates that he will need to meet  d2 - d3  with  e4xd3 , this means he will not be left with an isolated pawn. }
6. Nc2
6. Nf6
7. Nc3{ Now, Black has two choices on where to put the queen. According to the present state of theory,  e5  is the better square. I mostly agree, but while I think ... Qh5  is not best, I also think that it is tougher than its reputation. }
7. Qh5{ This is a very ambitious move. Black is hoping to get his bishop to  h3  to challenge its counterpart on  g2 . Since we anticipate that these bishops will be exchanged anyway, it makes no sense to waste a tempo on  Bf1 - g2  and White should instead aim to do something more productive. }
8. Ne3{ The plan is to attack the  e4 -pawn with  Qd1 - c2  next. It turns out to be less than trivial for Black to defend it. Additionally, we can also hope to play  Bf1 - g2  and meet  Bc8 - h3  with  Nc3xe4  without fearing the loss of a piece on  g2 . }
8. Bc5{ This is Black's main move. He is hoping to take the knight on  e3  to get access to the  f5 -square for his other bishop to keep the  e4 -pawn safe. Now, I like a move that aims to marginally improve upon the main line. }
9. Qa4{ In almost every single game, White has chosen to put the queen on  c2  instead. In general, I find  a4  to be a more active square, and it opens up some extra possibilities. Black is surely able to push us back to  c2  right away with  b7 - b5 , but I believe this move weakens his position. }
9. b5{ This seems like Black's best move. He kicks our queen right away without taking on  e3  first, which means we will have to come back to  c2  rather than the more desirable  b4  or  d4  squares. }
10. Qc2{ Now, Black has to figure out how to defend  e4 . I think his best coordination is to take on  e3 , bring his bishop to  f5 , and his queen to  g6 . }
10. Bxe3( { • }10...Bf5?! { Black will regret not taking on  e3  first. }11.Ncd5!± { Black is facing major tactical problems. } )( { • }10...Qg6? { Here we see the first instance of making Black regret putting his pawn on  b5 . }11.Nxb5!+- { Not only was this pawn tasty, Black is also facing colossal threats on the c-file. My machine claims he is absolutely busted. } )
11. fxe3{ Unlike what we have seen before, here White should capture with the f-pawn on  e3 . A good rule of thumb is that if your queen is on  c2 , you take back with the f-pawn, while if your queen is on  a4 , you take back with the d-pawn. These is no spot in the repertoire where this rule is not followed. }
11. Bf5
12. Bg2
12. Qg6{ This seems like the safest way for Black to bolster his e-pawn. }
13. O-O{ Now, sooner or later we will have to give an exchange on  f5 . There is no other way to activate the  g2 -bishop. Luckily, I think this works out nicely for White. }
13. O-O
14. Rxf5{ This is not White's only move by any stretch, but I am much happier grabbing the bishop right away. If Black is allowed to play  Rf8 - e8  to overprotect the  e4 -pawn, we will not be able to sacrifice on  f5  so easily. }
14. Qxf5
15. Nxe4{ I believe Black would be absolutely fine here if his pawn were back on  b7 . As is, the extra weakness on  c6  really matters. }
15. Re8
16. Nxf6+
16. Qxf6
17. d4{ Black will really struggle to develop his queenside, and in the meantime,  Bc1 - d2  and  a2 - a4  could come in short order. With the  c6 -pawn being as weak as it is, I have to prefer White here. }
