1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6( 2...c6 3.Nf3 e4 4.Nd4 d5 5.cxd5 Qxd5 6.e3 { This move does exist here, and I actually beat Karjakin with it at the 2021 World Cup. It's a little tricky, but Black can equalize. }( 6.Nc2! { As we saw in the 2...  c6  section, I believe this is the most challenging move. } )6...Bc5! { This move is annoying. }7.Nc3 Qe5 { And now, since Black got the bishop to  c5  in advance, my  f2 - f4  idea makes no sense. Black's queen will be able to go back to  e7  without blocking in the bishop. }8.f4? Qe7⩱ ( 8.d3 { This was the move I played, and it should be best. Black is still very much fine here, and my victory in the game cannot be attributed to any great opening idea. } ) )
3. Bg2
3. c6{ Playing ... c6  on the third move shares some similarities to what we saw previously with ... c6  on the second move, but there are some important differences as well. }
4. Nf3{ Again, I find this to be the most challenging way to play. }
4. e4( 4...d6 5.Nc3⩲ { This transposes to the 2...  c6   section . } )
5. Nd4
5. d5{ Now, just like we saw in the 2... c6  section, I like taking on  d5  immediately. }
6. cxd5
6. Qxd5{ Now, if we were to play  Nd4 - c2 , remaining consistent with the plan from the 2... c6  section, Black would be able to play  Qe5 - h5  with  Bc8 - h3  to follow, taking advantage of our spending a tempo on  Bf1 - g2 . So, we have to approach the position a bit differently. }( 6...cxd5? { As usual, this is wrong. After }7.d3 Bc5 8.Nb3 Bb6 9.O-O { we transpose to the 2...  c6   section , and White should have easy pressure against Black's center and a nice advantage. } )
7. e3{ I like this move now. Black should get his queen off the  d5 -square to make sure not to allow  d2 - d3  to become a problem. }
7. Qe5{ This is the main move, and now I like an interesting idea. }
8. f4{ This move only exists because Black chose a 2... Nf6  move order. This means that he did not get his bishop to  c5 , and he cannot coordinate nicely with the queen coming back to  e7  and the bishop already developed. As is,  Qe5 - e7  is probably the best move anyway, but this is obviously a step in the right direction for White. It's very surprising to me how rare this move is. }
8. Qe7{ This is the machine's recommendation. }
9. Nc3{ We are ready for  Qd1 - c2  next to scoop up the  e4 -pawn. }
9. Na6{ This is the move I would expect a human to make. Black anticipates the queen coming to  c2 , and gets ready with ... Nb4 . Now, in general, I think our plan should be to push  d2 - d3 , but I want to be a little patient first. }
10. O-O( 10.d3?! { I don't think we are ready for this yet. }10...Bg4! 11.Qd2 c5! 12.dxe4 cxd4 13.exd4 O-O-O! { In the same position with  g7 - g6  and  O-O  already included, I think Black would be in big trouble. Here, we are not as fast to develop our initiative, and I don't like that we have not castled yet. } )
10. Nc5( { After }10...Bg4 { , White plays }11.Qa4 { , }{ aiming to provoke the knight to  c5 . If Black goes there voluntarily, it is even worse. } )
11. Qc2{  b4  comes next to win the  e4 -pawn. }
11. a5
12. b3{  Ba3  is coming to remove the defender. Black will lose  e4 . }
