[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6( 2...c6 3.Nf3 e4 4.Nd4 d5 5.cxd5 Qxd5 6.e3 { This move does exist here, and I actually beat Karjakin with it at the 2021 World Cup. It's a little tricky, but Black can equalize. }( 6.Nc2! { As we saw in the 2...  c6  section, I believe this is the most challenging move. } )6...Bc5! { This move is annoying. }7.Nc3 Qe5 { And now, since Black got the bishop to  c5  in advance, my  f2 - f4  idea makes no sense. Black's queen will be able to go back to  e7  without blocking in the bishop. }8.f4? Qe7⩱ ( 8.d3 { This was the move I played, and it should be best. Black is still very much fine here, and my victory in the game cannot be attributed to any great opening idea. } ) )
3. Bg2
3. c6{ Playing ... c6  on the third move shares some similarities to what we saw previously with ... c6  on the second move, but there are some important differences as well. }
4. Nf3{ Again, I find this to be the most challenging way to play. }
4. e4( 4...d6 5.Nc3⩲ { This transposes to the 2...  c6   section . } )
5. Nd4
5. d5{ Now, just like we saw in the 2... c6  section, I like taking on  d5  immediately. }
6. cxd5
6. Qxd5{ Now, if we were to play  Nd4 - c2 , remaining consistent with the plan from the 2... c6  section, Black would be able to play  Qe5 - h5  with  Bc8 - h3  to follow, taking advantage of our spending a tempo on  Bf1 - g2 . So, we have to approach the position a bit differently. }( 6...cxd5? { As usual, this is wrong. After }7.d3 Bc5 8.Nb3 Bb6 9.O-O { we transpose to the 2...  c6   section , and White should have easy pressure against Black's center and a nice advantage. } )
7. e3{ I like this move now. Black should get his queen off the  d5 -square to make sure not to allow  d2 - d3  to become a problem. }
7. Qe5{ This is the main move, and now I like an interesting idea. }
8. f4{ This move only exists because Black chose a 2... Nf6  move order. This means that he did not get his bishop to  c5 , and he cannot coordinate nicely with the queen coming back to  e7  and the bishop already developed. As is,  Qe5 - e7  is probably the best move anyway, but this is obviously a step in the right direction for White. It's very surprising to me how rare this move is. }
8. exf3{ This feels like the most human response to me. Black should realize that the  e4 -pawn could become a weakness, and trading it off to force hanging pawns makes a lot of sense. Still, his position strikes me as difficult, and even if the machine is not that enthusiastic just yet, it does not surprise me that Black has scored half a point out of four in human encounters. }
9. Nxf3
9. Qh5
10. O-O
10. Bd6{ This novelty is Black's best move. It feels a little weird and overly ambitious, and it doesn't surprise me that in both games, Black chose to put the bishop on  e7  instead. }
11. Nc3
11. O-O
12. d4{ White is ready for  e3 - e4  next to take a massive share of the center. It is not too easy for Black to prevent. }
12. Re8{ This move is why it was so important for Black to put the bishop on  d6  rather than  e7 . he prevents  e3 - e4  for the moment. }
13. e4{ Or does he? Now, Black can equalize, but only with a very, very precise sequence, and then we still get a playable position. }
13. Nxe4{ He has to try. Allowing  e4 - e5  is not a winning proposition. Still, I could easily see a human failing to pull the trigger on this move against a blitzing opponent. }
14. Nxe4
14. Rxe4
15. Ne5{ Black's rook is trapped on  e4 . He has a whole bunch of ways to go down an exchange, but only one of them allows him to get a tenable position. I don't normally like playing for tricks and traps, but here Black has to walk a hell of a tightrope, and if he does, we still get a playable position. }
15. Qxd1
16. Rxd1{ Now, Black's rook is trapped. }
16. Bg4
17. Rd3{ Now, the rook is hit, and the bishop on  g4  is loose. }
17. Re1+( 17...Rxe5 18.dxe5 Bc7 19.Be3⩲ { again, Black should not have enough for the exchange here. } )
18. Kf2
18. Re2+{ Another tough move. }
19. Kf1
19. Rxg2{ There are so many other moments where Black can give an exchange and end up worse in the endgame. This is the only one where he is okay. Now, White has a choice. We can force a draw right now, accepting that Black found a novelty over half the game ago and prepared it perfectly to here, or play on in an interesting and unbalanced endgame. }
20. Kxg2( { I like keeping the game going. }20.Nxg4 { If you want to pull the emergency break, this is a draw. }20...Rc2! 21.h4! Na6 22.Ne3 Rh2 23.Kg1 Re2 24.Kf1= { White makes a perpetual against Black's rook. } )
20. Be6
21. Bf4
21. Na6
22. a3
22. Nc7
23. Ng6{ I like this move, exchanging off a set of minor pieces. I let my computer run here, and unsurprisingly, it landed on 0.00. A big part of modern preparation with White is judging which 0.00 positions feel playable and interesting, and which do not. Speaking totally honestly, this one is not super appealing to me. I don't think White is on the more pleasant side of equality or anything like that, but I do think you can still play. And while it is something of a cop-out, Black has to get here. We are now on move 23, and so far in human play, no Black player has made it to move 10. }
