[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. h6{ This move might look a little weird, but Black has a point. He makes a patient waiting move, asking us to make up our minds. If we play  Ng1 - f3 , then after  e5 - e4  and  d7 - d5 , Black is claiming that  h7 - h6  is more useful than  c7 - c6  would be. And, by not committing his knight to  c6  so soon, he is pointing out that we should be less inclined to bring our own knight to  c3 , as then  Bf8 - b4  would be possible without running into  Nc3 - d5 . Still, it feels a little too retro to me for Black to be able to move his h-pawn instead of fighting for the center and still manage to equalize. }
4. Nf3{ I like falling into Black's trap. We approach the position the same way we would if he had played  c7 - c6  instead. }
4. Nc6{ This really does not mesh well with  h7 - h6 . }
5. Nc3{ White is ready for  d2 - d4  next. As usual, we see that as soon as Black brings his knight to  c6 , we are happy to bring our own knight to  c3 . }
5. Bc5{ This is not merely a transposition to the Karpov System. White can punish Black directly. }
6. Nxe5
6. Nxe5
7. d4
7. Bd6{ Now, White would be pleasantly better if he took the knight, but he has something even more powerful. }
8. c5
8. Bxc5
9. dxc5{ Black can barely move, and White is much better. Sooner or later, I would expect  d7 - d5  to come, because how else can he ever develop his bishop? Then when White takes on  d6 , he will have a monster bishop pair and Black will have an isolated d-pawn. }
