[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. h6{ This move might look a little weird, but Black has a point. He makes a patient waiting move, asking us to make up our minds. If we play  Ng1 - f3 , then after  e5 - e4  and  d7 - d5 , Black is claiming that  h7 - h6  is more useful than  c7 - c6  would be. And, by not committing his knight to  c6  so soon, he is pointing out that we should be less inclined to bring our own knight to  c3 , as then  Bf8 - b4  would be possible without running into  Nc3 - d5 . Still, it feels a little too retro to me for Black to be able to move his h-pawn instead of fighting for the center and still manage to equalize. }
4. Nf3{ I like falling into Black's trap. We approach the position the same way we would if he had played  c7 - c6  instead. }
4. e4( 4...d6?! 5.d4!± { White already has a very nice position. Black probably will end up in a rotten version of the Old Indian. } )
5. Nd4
5. Nc6{ This strikes me as Black's best way to take advantage of omitting the move  c7 - c6 . }
6. Nc2
6. Bc5{ This is also possible, aiming for  Qe7  next to bolster the  e4 -pawn. But I don't buy it. }
7. Nc3
7. Qe7
8. O-O
8. O-O
9. Ne3{ This is a huge problem for Black to deal with.  Ned5  is coming to remove the defender and then  e4  will drop. }
9. Bxe3( { What else? }9...d6 10.Ned5 Nxd5 11.cxd5± {  e4  falls and White will be a clean pawn up. } )
10. fxe3{ White has an easy plan for all of his pieces, and his position more or less plays itself. Black will definitely lose  e4 . }
