[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 2...Nf6 3.Bg2 d5"]
[Black "6...Be7 7.Nc3 Be6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5{ This is a very ambitious move from Black, and one of the biggest mainlines after 1.  c4   e5 . He invites us straight into a reverse open Sicilian. Our extra tempo means we never have to worry about anything, but is the Sicilian so good that with a tempo up, we are actually better? Black is arguing that this is not the case. When you dig deep enough into the positions, I do think he holds together, but I found a lot of ways to put his position under pressure. }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. Nf3
5. Nc6
6. O-O{ I think this is a very important move, and this position is one of the reasons I like playing 2.  g3  more than 2.  Nc3 . }( 6.Nc3 { This might look like it transposes to all of the same main lines we will see later on, but in fact, I think it allows Black an easy route to equality. }6...Bc5! { I could not find a thing for White in these positions once Black develops the bishop to the more ambitious  c5 -square. I beat David Navara from this position with Black, and while the position is surely playable, I think Black equalizes without much trouble. I do not like that he is able to avoid moving his  d5 -knight and continue development without losing time. } )
6. Be7{ For some time, this move was considered to be inaccurate due to White being able to push  d2 - d4  here. I am actually not convinced that this is so great for us, and I'd rather stick with  Nc3 , aiming to reach the main line. }
7. Nc3{ Black should play  Nd5 - b6 , transposing to the mainlines. Other moves are not to be recommended. }
7. Be6{ This is way too ambitious.  Be2  and  Be3  is not the best way to play against the Accelerated Dragon thanks to a quick  d7 - d5  coming, and here White is even up an additional tempo. }( { • }7...Nb6 8.a3 { This transposes to the mainlines. } )( { • }7...Nxc3 { This is foolish. There is no reason for Black to strengthen White's center control like this. }8.bxc3 O-O 9.d4⩲ { White is pleasantly better thanks to the big center. } )( { • }7...Nf6 { This move is possible, and Black is hoping to argue that we have put the knight on  c3  rather than  d2 , forcing us into a different development scheme that what I wanted against 6...  Nf6 . Even still, this is unconvincing. After }8.b4!? { it transposes to  the mainline . } )
8. d4
8. exd4
9. Nxd4{  Nb5  is a fancy alternative, but I find the simple move to be quite sufficient. Black has some problems to solve here. }
9. Nxd4{ If Black had already castled here, he would be basically okay. But, since he is playing a normal mainline position with a tempo less, he is not already castled, and White can bring the pain. }
10. Bxd5
10. Bxd5
11. Qxd4{ Black will lose his  g7 -pawn, and he will have a bad day. }
