1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5{ This is a very ambitious move from Black, and one of the biggest mainlines after 1.  c4   e5 . He invites us straight into a reverse open Sicilian. Our extra tempo means we never have to worry about anything, but is the Sicilian so good that with a tempo up, we are actually better? Black is arguing that this is not the case. When you dig deep enough into the positions, I do think he holds together, but I found a lot of ways to put his position under pressure. }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. Nf3
5. Nc6
6. O-O{ I think this is a very important move, and this position is one of the reasons I like playing 2.  g3  more than 2.  Nc3 . }( 6.Nc3 { This might look like it transposes to all of the same main lines we will see later on, but in fact, I think it allows Black an easy route to equality. }6...Bc5! { I could not find a thing for White in these positions once Black develops the bishop to the more ambitious  c5 -square. I beat David Navara from this position with Black, and while the position is surely playable, I think Black equalizes without much trouble. I do not like that he is able to avoid moving his  d5 -knight and continue development without losing time. } )
