9. Re8{ The plan with  Re8  and  Bf8  tends to work really nicely whenever White commits his bishop to  e3 , but playing it before the bishop commits strikes me as somewhat premature. The reason is that once Black plays  Be7 - f8  next, we will be able to provoke a weakening in his position with  Bc1 - g5 . }
10. Rb1{ I like making another patient waiting move. This is not particularly subtle, White wants to play  b2 - b4  next and be in better shape to deal with  a7 - a5  in response. }
10. a5{ This move has seen some play as well. It makes sense, preventing  b2 - b4  forcefully. But it also makes a weakness. }
11. Be3
11. Bf8{ Now it makes sense to bring the bishop back to  f8  since we cannot go  Bg5  any more. If Black got one more move,  Nc6 - d4  would come, equalizing without much trouble. I think we can change the character of the game. }
12. Bxb6{ White takes advantage of  a7 - a5  weakening the position. Black is unable to take back with the a-pawn on  b6 . }
12. cxb6
13. Nd2
13. Be6
14. Rc1{ The computer thinks Black is just about okay here. In human terms, I definitely think White should be better. We have a very simple plan to play  Nc4 ,  Qa4 ,  e3 ,  Rfd1 . We will have very good play on the light squares. While the computer is not impressed with White's position, it also suggests that Black's best move is  Re8 - e7 . Who plays such a move? It feels so much harder to handle this position from the black side. }
