[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5{ This is a very ambitious move from Black, and one of the biggest mainlines after 1.  c4   e5 . He invites us straight into a reverse open Sicilian. Our extra tempo means we never have to worry about anything, but is the Sicilian so good that with a tempo up, we are actually better? Black is arguing that this is not the case. When you dig deep enough into the positions, I do think he holds together, but I found a lot of ways to put his position under pressure. }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. Nf3
5. Nc6
6. O-O{ I think this is a very important move, and this position is one of the reasons I like playing 2.  g3  more than 2.  Nc3 . }( 6.Nc3 { This might look like it transposes to all of the same main lines we will see later on, but in fact, I think it allows Black an easy route to equality. }6...Bc5! { I could not find a thing for White in these positions once Black develops the bishop to the more ambitious  c5 -square. I beat David Navara from this position with Black, and while the position is surely playable, I think Black equalizes without much trouble. I do not like that he is able to avoid moving his  d5 -knight and continue development without losing time. } )
6. Nb6{ This is the main move by far. Now, in recent times White has tried to be a little tricky with  b2 - b3  here. I played this move myself, and won a nice game. But Black has figured out how to hold on there, and I like sticking with the tried and true old main line. }
7. Nc3{ As we said  here , now that Black has agreed not to put his bishop on  c5 , I am happy to commit the knight to  c3 . }
7. Be7
8. a3( 8.d3 { This is a fine move order as well. }8...O-O 9.a3  )
8. O-O( 8...a5 { In general, I think advancing  a7 - a5  is not Black's best idea in this line. }9.d3 O-O 10.Be3 { This transposes to the 9...  a5   line . } )
9. d3{ I like combining  d3  and  a3  like this. White is a little bit patient with the  c1 -bishop, and can choose later which square it wants to go to. Now, it is important to understand a couple points. First off, while we do not necessarily always want to push  b2 - b4 , in can come up in some places, and as such Black often plays  a7 - a5  at some moment or another. Whenever this happens, it should immediately tip us off to the potential to play  Bc1 - e3  and grab the knight on  b6 .     Secondly, Black's best plans usually involve preventing  b4  by tactical means, hoping that he can push  a7 - a5  in response and start attacking our queenside. As such, we should be careful to only push  b2 - b4  when ready. Thirdly, if we ever put our bishop on  e3 , Black's best plan is probably to play  Rf8 - e8 ,  Be7 - f8 , and  Nc6 - d4 . If we wait with the bishop, we can meet  Be7 - f8  with  Bc1 - g5 . }
9. Re8{ The plan with  Re8  and  Bf8  tends to work really nicely whenever White commits his bishop to  e3 , but playing it before the bishop commits strikes me as somewhat premature. The reason is that once Black plays  Be7 - f8  next, we will be able to provoke a weakening in his position with  Bc1 - g5 . }
10. Rb1{ I like making another patient waiting move. This is not particularly subtle, White wants to play  b2 - b4  next and be in better shape to deal with  a7 - a5  in response. }
10. Bf8{ This is Black's most consistent reply, and has been his most common move in practice. Now, I like provoking a weakness in the position. }
11. Bg5{ Black is not thrilled about having to advance  f7 - f6 . But putting the queen on  d7  is not too appealing either. }
11. f6
12. Be3{ Now, Black's normal equalizing idea would be to play  Nc6 - d4 , trading off the bad knight. Here, we will see that provoking  f7 - f6  makes it harder to comfortably do so. }
12. Nd4
13. b4
13. Bg4( { This would normally be Black's best move. }13...a5 14.Bxd4! exd4 15.Nb5 { Black is losing the  d4 -pawn. } )
14. Bxd4
14. exd4
15. Ne4
15. c6
16. Nc5{ It's really nice that we have a check on  b3  in the back pocket. Black is much worse. }
16. Nd5
17. Nxd4{ No need to fear the knight coming to  c3 . It was important to provoke  f7 - f6 ! }
