10. Be3{ When we consider that Black's best plan against  Be3  is to play  Re8 ,  Bf8 , and  Nd4 , bringing the bishop to  e3  now makes perfect sense. The bishop on  e6  is in the way, and it means that the  e5 -pawn will be loose. }
10. Re8{ This move makes a lot less sense now that Black is unable to get  Bf8  and  Nd4  in. Let's see what happens if he tries anyway. }
11. Rc1
11. h6{ This would be the consistent move, aiming for  Bf8  to come next without a disaster on  g5 . }
12. Ne4
12. Bf8{ Now, Black is just about ready for  Nc6 - d4  to come next, equalizing. But he is too slow. }
13. Bc5{ Playing  Be3 - c5  to trade dark squared bishops and weaken the  c5  square is a key theme in this line. In this case, White was just in time to do so without allowing Black to get  Nc6 - d4  in first. }
