7. Nc3{ As we said  here , now that Black has agreed not to put his bishop on  c5 , I am happy to commit the knight to  c3 . }
7. Be7
8. a3( 8.d3 { This is a fine move order as well. }8...O-O 9.a3  )
8. O-O( 8...a5 { In general, I think advancing  a7 - a5  is not Black's best idea in this line. }9.d3 O-O 10.Be3 { This transposes to the 9...  a5   line . } )
9. d3{ I like combining  d3  and  a3  like this. White is a little bit patient with the  c1 -bishop, and can choose later which square it wants to go to. Now, it is important to understand a couple points. First off, while we do not necessarily always want to push  b2 - b4 , in can come up in some places, and as such Black often plays  a7 - a5  at some moment or another. Whenever this happens, it should immediately tip us off to the potential to play  Bc1 - e3  and grab the knight on  b6 .     Secondly, Black's best plans usually involve preventing  b4  by tactical means, hoping that he can push  a7 - a5  in response and start attacking our queenside. As such, we should be careful to only push  b2 - b4  when ready. Thirdly, if we ever put our bishop on  e3 , Black's best plan is probably to play  Rf8 - e8 ,  Be7 - f8 , and  Nc6 - d4 . If we wait with the bishop, we can meet  Be7 - f8  with  Bc1 - g5 . }
9. Be6{ This is Black's main and best move. One of the biggest appeals is that it discourages us from continuing with  b2 - b4 , as then after  a7 - a5  and  Nc6 - d4 , we won't be able to take on  e5  thanks to annoying threats on the  b3 -square. So, we look in a different direction. }
10. Be3{ When we consider that Black's best plan against  Be3  is to play  Re8 ,  Bf8 , and  Nd4 , bringing the bishop to  e3  now makes perfect sense. The bishop on  e6  is in the way, and it means that the  e5 -pawn will be loose. }
10. f5{ Since the  Re8  and  Bf8  plan makes less sense once Black has committed the bishop to the  e6 -square, Black generally switches gears and aims for kingside advances. After all, the bishop on  e3  sort of seems like it is begging for  f5 - f4 . }( 10...a5 11.Bxb6 { Transposes to the 9...  a5  line. } )
11. Rc1{ Now, Black should be a bit patient about pushing  f5 - f4 . Doing so right away would weaken the  e4 -square, and it makes more sense to wait for  Nc3 - a4  to come first. }
11. Bf6{ I was surprised to find that this is Black's most common move. It seems really inconsistent with the plan of playing for a kingside attack, and White is immediately given access to the  c5 -square. }
12. Bc5
12. Rf7
13. e4{ I like this move a lot. In general, in any kind of dragon, the exchange of the f-pawn for the e-pawn like this should heavily favor the dragon side, which in this case is us. }
13. Rd7
14. exf5
14. Bxf5
15. Ne1{ Even with a passive knight, White is still pleasantly better with  Nc3 - e4  and  b2 - b4  on the way. }
