14. Qxa4{ The computer swears this position is equal, but it looks a bit unpleasant for Black to me. White has a simple plan to put his bishop on  c5 , trade dark squared bishops, get the rook to  c5 , and play on the c-file. Eventually,  Nf3 - d2  can become a factor as well, pressuring the long diagonal. Despite the machine's insistence that Black is fine, it looks much easier to handle from the white side, and I find it unsurprising that Black's score in practice has been very poor. We will see  a nice game  from Anand in the illustrative games section that highlights the strategic dangers Black can face. }
